</caption>
<subSubSection id="C32A653EBD66294764E6FEAF2A2F8B85" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F36B5BD66294764E6FEAF28588F95" blockId="38.[164,779,198,495]" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD66294764AAFEAF2A2D8F42" baseAuthorityName="Disney &amp; Ellwood" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[240,382,290,312]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Metopininae">Metopininae</taxonomicName>
includes about 180 of the approximately 290 genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD66294765C8FECD2AA48F2C" authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1833" box="[402,503,320,342]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phoridae</taxonomicName>
. We have observed much unexplored variation in thoracic morphology that will be useful to establish the relationships within the metopinines. Targeting a better understanding of the evolution of these structures at the base of the family, we chose not to explore the group until a later time.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F36B5BD66294764FEFD8A2A398C46" blockId="38.[164,778,519,572]" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">
30. Proepimeron: (0) small, (1) greatly expanded (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD6629476486FDAB2A0D8C46" box="[220,350,550,572]" captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="39.[144,223,1813,1832]" captionTargetBox="[149,1419,196,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-0@39.[146,1422,194,1783]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figure 33 Character 30. Proepimeron small (0); proepimeron greatly expanded (1). A, Chonocephalus. B, Javanoxenia. C, Phora. D, Phlebothrix. E, Beckerina. F, Apocephalus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333700/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 33A–F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F36B5BD66294764E6FDD92A698A96" blockId="38.[164,779,596,1260]" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">
This feature, diagnostic of the metopinines, has been referred to as ‘anepisternal furrow present’ and is a uniquely derived character of the subfamily. This modification possibly corresponds to the enlargement of the proepimeron dorsally and posteriorly, moving with it the surrounding suture. In platypezids (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD662947660CFD6129C18D79" box="[598,658,748,771]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[164,243,946,965]" captionText="Figure 2 SEM of thorax of Protoclythia (Platypezidae), lateral view." pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and other brachycerans (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD662947651DFC862AD78D5B" box="[327,388,779,801]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[144,226,1409,1428]" captionTargetBox="[147,1419,199,1378]" captionTargetId="figure-116@3.[144,1424,194,1379]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1 Lateral view of the thorax of Cyclotelus (Therevidae). Abbreviations: AnII, anterior anepisternum II; AnIII, metanepisternum; AnP, posterior anepisternum; Ap, antepronotum; CeS, cervical sclerite; CxI, forecoxa; CxII, midcoxa; Cx III, hind coxa; EsI, proepisternum I; Em I, proepimeron I; Em II (Ae), anepimeron II; Em II (Ke), katepimeron II; Em III, epimeron III; KtII, katepisternum (= mesokatepisternum); KtIII, metakatepisternum; Lt, laterotergite; Md, mediotergite; MeII, meron; Pp, postpronotum; PtII, mesopleurotrochantin; RR, paratergite; ScIII, metascutum; TgII, mesothoracic tegula." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333619/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), the proepimeron is already fused to the anepisternum, with the suture scarcely visible, which is also the condition in most phorids (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD66294766C4FCC52BE58D07" captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="39.[144,223,1813,1832]" captionTargetBox="[149,1419,196,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-0@39.[146,1422,194,1783]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figure 33 Character 30. Proepimeron small (0); proepimeron greatly expanded (1). A, Chonocephalus. B, Javanoxenia. C, Phora. D, Phlebothrix. E, Beckerina. F, Apocephalus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333700/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 33A– C</figureCitation>
) except the metopinines. The prothorax pleural suture is just dorsal to the insertion of the forecoxa, the anepisternal furrow being placed more posteriorly. The suture of the ‘anepisternal furrow’, and hence is secondary, but it apparently delimits the proepimeron, which would be greatly enlarged in all metopinines (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD66294764F6FB932A638A4F" box="[172,304,1054,1077]" captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="39.[144,223,1813,1832]" captionTargetBox="[149,1419,196,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-0@39.[146,1422,194,1783]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figure 33 Character 30. Proepimeron small (0); proepimeron greatly expanded (1). A, Chonocephalus. B, Javanoxenia. C, Phora. D, Phlebothrix. E, Beckerina. F, Apocephalus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333700/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 33D–F</figureCitation>
). Another genus of phorids that appears to have a version of this furrow (under light microscopy) is the phorine genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD662947659EFBD1290B8A0B" authorityName="Beyer" authorityYear="1965" box="[452,600,1116,1137]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Mannheimsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAA7BD662947659EFBD1290B8A0B" box="[452,600,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Mannheimsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the ‘furrow’ is not visible in our SEMs, differently from true metopinines. We thus conclude that the state in 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD66294764FEFB3A2A128AB6" authorityName="Beyer" authorityYear="1965" box="[164,321,1207,1228]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Mannheimsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAA7BD66294764FEFB3A2A128AB6" box="[164,321,1207,1228]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Mannheimsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not homologous to that found in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD66294764FEFB5B2A648A96" baseAuthorityName="Disney &amp; Ellwood" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[164,311,1238,1260]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Metopininae">Metopininae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F36B5BD66294764FEFA8928588B43" blockId="38.[164,779,1284,1337]" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">
31. Dorsal separation of katepisternum from anepimeron: (0) clearly visible, (1) lost (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD66294766DEFAAF28538B43" box="[644,768,1314,1337]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="40.[164,240,1816,1835]" captionTargetBox="[169,1439,197,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-0@40.[166,1441,195,1786]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figure 34 Character 31. Dorsal separation of katepisternum from anepimeron clearly visible (0); suture lost (1). A, Phlebothrix. B, Brownphora. C, Beckerina. D, Gymnophora. E, Apodicrania. F, Trophodeinus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333704/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 34A–F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F36B5BD66294764E6FADD2A2F8B85" blockId="38.[164,779,1360,1535]" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">
This character is in its primitive character state, within the metopinines, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD6629476592FAE229D18BFE" authorityName="Liu" authorityYear="1996" box="[456,642,1391,1412]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Ctenopleuriphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAA7BD6629476592FAE229D18BFE" box="[456,642,1391,1412]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Ctenopleuriphora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD66294766D5FAE228588BFE" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1969" box="[655,779,1391,1412]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Phlebothrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAA7BD66294766D5FAE228588BFE" box="[655,779,1391,1412]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Phlebothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C304D36BD6629476482FA032A358BD9" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="2004" box="[216,358,1422,1443]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Brownphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B944EAA7BD6629476482FA032A358BD9" box="[216,358,1422,1443]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Brownphora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD662947652CFA032AA98BD9" box="[374,506,1422,1444]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="40.[164,240,1816,1835]" captionTargetBox="[169,1439,197,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-0@40.[166,1441,195,1786]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figure 34 Character 31. Dorsal separation of katepisternum from anepimeron clearly visible (0); suture lost (1). A, Phlebothrix. B, Brownphora. C, Beckerina. D, Gymnophora. E, Apodicrania. F, Trophodeinus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333704/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 34A, B</figureCitation>
). Its apomorphic condition (
<figureCitation id="130B2A30BD6629476485FA212A088BB8" box="[223,347,1452,1474]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="40.[164,240,1816,1835]" captionTargetBox="[169,1439,197,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-0@40.[166,1441,195,1786]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figure 34 Character 31. Dorsal separation of katepisternum from anepimeron clearly visible (0); suture lost (1). A, Phlebothrix. B, Brownphora. C, Beckerina. D, Gymnophora. E, Apodicrania. F, Trophodeinus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5333704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5333704/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="462">Fig. 34C–F</figureCitation>
) is shared by most other metopinines. The plesiomorphic condition is widespread in phorines and other phorids.
</paragraph>
